ing’.","History: Peter Bulkeley (1583–1659), Puritan divine, who came from Bedfordshire, England, was a founder of Concord, MA, in 1636."],"variants":[{"name":"Bulkley","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Bulkeley  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Bulkeley was born in 1310, in Norbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Bulkeley, was 20 and her mother, Maude Davenport, was 8. She married Roger Bulkeley in 1334, in Nantwich, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1269–1313":"1269–1313","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1320–1360":"1320–1360","–Male":"Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1290–1326":"1290–1326","1302–1326":"1302–1326","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1335":"1335","1302":"1302","1313":"1313","1269":"1269","1334":"1334","1355":"1355","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Nantwich, C